</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E298EC469E9773AC28FF2F78585A35CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="125" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="4B73094B83822CF7ABA4E5A3710B14BD" pageId="0" pageNumber="125">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A3A9C55B32E5FE6757E64370D80E562D" pageId="0" pageNumber="125">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="3207DF5802A10D7DF87BC34503023B7B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="125">apic</emphasis>
- (adj., apical) and 
<emphasis id="5F1C13CBE639A9A100B75B123E7A158A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="125">curvatus</emphasis>
(adj., curved), referring to the valva curved dorsally at almost a right angle in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
